Response:

The system of position constraint equations for the piston crank system is as derived in the lecture. Once we have established $\vec{C}\left(\vec{q}, t\right)$, and solved for $\vec{q}$ at each time step of the desired range, the process for finding the speeds of the moving parts follows the same framework demonstrated with the Flappy Bird example/in previous lectures. We compute the Jacobian $C_q = \frac{\partial \vec{C}}{\partial \vec{q}}$ and the partial time derivative vector $\vec{C}_t = \frac{\partial \vec{C}}{\partial t}$, then solve the velocity equation $C_q \dot{\vec{q}} = - \vec{C}_t$. At each time step, we first solve the nonlinear constraint equations for the positions, then substitute those values into the Jacobian $(C_q)$ and the partial time derivative vector $(\vec{C}_t)$, and then solve the resulting linear system for $\dot{\vec{q}}$. This is powerful because it is scalable, regardless of how many constraints and degrees of freedom a system has, as long as the number of constraints equals the number of DOFs, the positions and velocities can be found at each time step using this framework. Furthermore, when solving for the positions and velocities at each time step, the problem reduces to nonlinear and linear algebra, respectively, with no differential equations required. As for alternative Flappy Bird paths, you could swap out either or both of the constraints. The geometric constraint $y = \sin{\pi x}$ defines the shape of the path, and the driving constraint $x = 2t$ dictates how the bird moves along it. For the path shape, another option we could try would be $y = A\sin{\pi x} \cdot e^{-\alpha x}$ for a decaying oscillation where the bird's up and down motion gradually flattens out. For the driving constraint, we could use $x = t^2$ to have the bird accelerate. 

